V!Traveling while abroad\u000a!!!!Important things to keep in mind when planning travel\u000aMany programs may provide opportunities for independent travel. First, always ''keep your <<if $facultyled>>faculty leader<<else>>resident director or program staff<</if>> informed'' of your travel. Don't forget to keep your family in the loop; if there is an emergency back home, they will want to know how to get in touch with you.\u000a<div class="talkbox">\u000a|box|k\u000a|!COVID-19 Considerations|\u000a|You cannot count on being able to travel to other countries independently while you are on your program. There may be restrictions on non-essential travel between countries, even within normally open regional blocs like the EU. New restrictions could be put in place at any time, including while you are traveling! Your program may also impose restrictions out of an abundance of caution.|\u000a|Even if travel is possible, it may be more difficult than before. Before you set out, be sure that you understand requirements to enter other countries as well as requirements to return to your host country. Always carry your essential travel documents when you travel, including passport and proof of vaccination!|\u000a</div>\u000aSome countries that you plan to visit may have different entry requirements than your primary host country. ''Investigate all the countries you're interested in'' before you leave the US. If any require a <span title="A stamp or sticker placed in your passport that allows you to enter a foreign country.">travel visa</span>, it will probably be easier to get the visa while you're in the US--this applies to both international students and US citizens!\u000a\u000aIn every country you visit, make a point of knowing where your ''home country's nearest embassy or consulate'' is. You want to know where you can find support if you get into real trouble. (If you're a US citizen, you should bookmark the [[list of US embassies around the world|http://www.usembassy.gov/]].)\u000a\u000aAs you make travel plans, consider the ''ecological impact'' of your travel. Per person, [[airplane travel|https://www.theguardian.com/environment/ng-interactive/2019/jul/19/carbon-calculator-how-taking-one-flight-emits-as-much-as-many-people-do-in-a-year]] generally emits far more carbon dioxide into the atmosphere than travel by train, bus, or automobile. Think about whether you really need to leave your host city so often, and about whether you can use alternative transport that would reduce your carbon footprint.\u000a\u000aFinally, independent travel is one of the ''most expensive activities'' you can undertake abroad. Be sure to budget appropriately, and remember to consider safety while you're on the lookout for ways to travel on the cheap.\u000a<<if not $facultyled>><div class="talkbox">\u000a|box|k\u000a|!Wisdom from alums|\u000a|Every year, students tell us that while they loved the traveling they did abroad, they also regretted not getting to know their host city better. Consider the value of staying put sometimes rather than skipping town.|\u000a</div><</if>>\u000a\u000a<<segue "Identity and diversity">>\u005c
