V<<if $facultyled>><<sidebar "When and how to contact Vanderbilt">><<else>><<sidebar "When to contact GEO">><</if>>\u000aMost of the time, your most appropriate contact abroad will be your <<if $facultyled>>faculty leader or on-site staff<<else>>resident director, or if you are an exchange student, an advisor in your host university's international office<</if>>. But there may also be times when it makes more sense to reach out to Vanderbilt<<if $facultyled>>. Who you contact depends on which college is offering your course; see the chart below!\u000a\u000a<<display "Faculty-Led Administration">><<else>> and GEO. See the chart for things that GEO is well prepared to help you with!\u000a\u000a|box|k\u000a|!What GEO Can Help You With|\u000a|You are uncomfortable discussing an issue with your on-site staff|\u000a|Questions about specific Vanderbilt policies|\u000a|Questions about billing|\u000a|Questions about your transcript|\u000a|You want to remain abroad for another term|\u000a|You're just not sure who to talk to!|<</if>>\u005c\u000a\u000aIf you are facing a health or safety issue or emergency, you can contact ''Vanderbilt Incident Response for Travel'' (VIRT). VIRT is available around the clock and can help with many health and safety issues.\u000a\u000a<<display "VIRT contact info">>\u005c\u000a\u000a<<segue "Phones and internet abroad">>
