V!Contacts and communications\u000a!!!!Who should I contact for help abroad?\u000aCommunications abroad can seem difficult at first. You need to learn who your best resources are, as well as figure out the most convenient methods of communication within your host country and back home.\u000a\u000aYour <<if $facultyled>>''faculty leader''<<else>>''resident director''<</if>> will be your most reliable contact person: knowledgeable about the program, the host country, and the city. Whether you have a basic question, a scheduling conundrum, or are in the midst of an emergency, your <<if $facultyled>>faculty leader<<else>>resident director<</if>> and on-site staff should be the ''first person you contact.'' You will find out more about who your contact(s) should be in your program-specific predeparture orientation.\u000a\u000aIf you are traveling away from your site or your <<if $facultyled>>faculty leader<<else>>resident director<</if>> is not available, you may want to contact Vanderbilt for help. In particular, if you are in an emergency situation or facing a health issue, you can contact  Vanderbilt Incident Response for Travel (VIRT) at +1 615-322-2745.\u000a\u000a<<sidebar-box "Hm...">>\u000a   [[When should I contact Vanderbilt or the Global Education Office?|When to contact Vanderbilt]]\u000a<</sidebar-box>>\u000a\u000a<<segue "Phones and internet abroad">>
