V!Disabilities and accommodations\u000a!!!!Getting physical and academic accommodations\u000aIf you have registered with Vanderbilt [[Student Access|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/student-access/]] to receive academic or physical accommodations at Vanderbilt, you will want to learn whether you can get similar accommodations on your program abroad.\u000a\u000aConsult with Student Access staff and request that they send your accommodations letter to your <<if $facultyled>>faculty leader<<else>>program advisor or  on-site staff<</if>>. Do this //before// you depart! Program staff will use this letter in researching what accommodations are possible on site.\u000a\u000aIf you have a disability or challenge that you have so far managed without Student Access, you may want to meet with them before you study abroad. In addition to providing you with a letter, they can help you think through what you might need to ask of your program staff abroad.\u000a\u000aDo understand that while most requests will be honored, laws in other countries regarding required or reasonable accommodations often differ from what is mandated by law in the United States. ''Not all requests can be met exactly.'' For example, the legal status of emotional support animals varies around the world; it may be extremely difficult to incorporate an emotional support animal into many study abroad experiences, depending on the location and specific characteristics of the program.\u000a\u000a|box|k\u000a|!Resources|\u000a|[[Vanderbilt Student Access|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/student-access/]]|\u000a|[[Mobility International USA|http://www.miusa.org/]], resources for travelers with disabilities|\u000a|[[Travelers with Disabilities|http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/yellowbook/2014/chapter-8-advising-travelers-with-specific-needs/travelers-with-disabilities]], excellent information on traveling with physical disabilities|\u000a\u000a<<segue "Money">>\u005c
