V!Living abroad\u000a!!!!Considerations for life abroad in 2022\u000aMost countries outside the United States have taken more top-down approaches to COVID-19 than the US. Many will have both national and local regulations to follow. Wherever you go, you are likely to find somewhat different COVID rules and more nuance in how those are applied.\u000a\u000aIn particular, response to COVID outbreaks is more likely to involve strict, if temporary, ''lockdowns and targeted shutdowns of services''. These may cause inconvenience, including interrupting classes or travel. It is possible that your coursework might need to go online for an extended period, or that a planned trip may have to be canceled.\u000a\u000aYour university or program will provide guidance on rules and regulations throughout your semester for your host site. If you are looking to travel elsewhere, however, you\u2019ll need to keep up with this information--and travel-specific restrictions--yourself. Consider consulting with Vanderbilt's [[Office of Global Safety|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/global/global-safety/]] on any independent travel plans.\u000a\u000aWith independent travel likely restricted in many places, ''GEO encourages you to explore your host city and region''. There is a lot to be said for getting to know one area in depth: you develop a more intimate relationship with your surroundings, gain a deeper understanding of the local culture and rhythms of life, and are more likely to begin to see how to live more like locals do. The feeling of competence of mastering the ins and outs of another city is very satisfying.\u000a\u000a''Make use of your program staff\u2019s intimate knowledge of your host city''. They can help you find cool things to do, master transport systems, find safe routes to where you want to go, and more!\u000a\u000aIf your program allows you to live in ''independent housing'', consider carefully. While the freedom of independent housing may be attractive, there are downsides as well. These include the difficulty of navigating unfamiliar regulations and requirements (perhaps in a foreign language), the possibility of predatory landlords, and the difficulty of researching and assessing safety from abroad. One upside is that it can be a real learning experience to navigate the process of finding and renting your own place. If you are finding your own housing, remember that you need to turn in your Study Abroad Housing Policy Waiver Form to GEO before your program begins\u2014and that ''you aren\u2019t cleared to study abroad until we receive it!''\u000a/% !Where will you live?\u000a!!!!<<if $facultyled and ($maymester or $summer)>>Will you need housing on-campus at Vanderbilt?<<else>>What choices do you have in your housing abroad?<</if>>\u000aSome programs offer you the opportunity to select from multiple housing options, including in some cases the option to live in independent housing. <<if not $facultyled>>Which should you choose?\u000a\u000aThe answer, of course, depends on what you are hoping to get out of your time overseas. (If you're not sure what your housing options are, talk to the GEO advisor for your program.)\u000a\u000aBut since you may be facing a choice soon, we want to share with you ''what alumni of Vanderbilt study abroad tell us'' in their program evaluations: Students who live with natives of their host country typically report greater satisfaction with their housing and integration into the local culture than students who live with Americans. This is true whether students lived with a homestay family or with native roommates of their own age.\u000a<<display "Housing chart">>\u000aIf your program allows you to live in ''independent housing'', consider carefully. While the freedom of independent housing may be attractive, there are downsides as well. These include the difficulty of navigating unfamiliar regulations and requirements (perhaps in a foreign language), the possibility of predatory landlords, and the difficulty of researching and assessing safety from abroad. One upside is that it can be a real learning experience to navigate the process of finding and renting your own place. If you are finding your own housing, remember that you need to turn in your Study Abroad Housing Policy Waiver Form to GEO before your program begins\u2014and that you aren\u2019t cleared to study abroad until we receive it!\u005c\u000a<<else>>Students on most faculty-led summer courses will live in hotels, hostels, or in the residence halls of partner universities. You will receive more information about housing abroad from your faculty leader.<<if $summer or $maymester>>\u000a\u000aIf a component of your program is based at Vanderbilt, ''you are responsible for finding your own housing in Nashville''. Vanderbilt's [[Office of Housing and Residential Education|http://www.vanderbilt.edu/ResEd/main/]] does make housing available to students whose programs are partially taught abroad, but an advance application is required.\u000a\u000aApplications for Maymester/Summer housing are generally made available in mid-April, and move-in is usually on or around the day that residence halls close to non-graduating students. You will be charged a standard daily rate. [[Contact|http://www.vanderbilt.edu/ResEd/main/contact-us/contact-us/]] the Office of Housing and Residential Education for more information.\u000a<</if>><</if>>\u000a<<if $shortterm>>\u000aBy the way, are you ''thinking about doing a semester abroad in the future?'' Here's something that you might want to consider: Students who live with natives of their host country typically report greater satisfaction with their housing and integration into the local culture than students who live with Americans. This is true whether students lived with a homestay family or with native roommates of their own age.\u000a<<display "Housing chart">><</if>>\u005c %/\u000a   \u000a<<segue "Eating and diet">>\u005c
