V<<sidebar "Where to find crucial information about your medications">>\u000aThere are two pieces of information that will be useful or even critical for you to know about your medications: the legal status of the drug in your host country, and the generic/chemical name and/or the local brand names it goes by.\u000a\u000aTo ''find out if any of your medications are restricted or banned'' in your host country, contact the country's embassy here in the US. The US Department of State provides a [[directory of foreign embassies|https://travel.state.gov/content/travel/en/consularnotification/ConsularNotificationandAccess.html]]. Even some over-the-counter drugs may be more restricted abroad, so ask if you have doubts. In some cases, GEO may be able to advise you on whether your prescriptions are legal to carry abroad. Contact your GEO advisor or Vanderbilt's [[Office of Global Safety|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/global/global-safety/]].\u000a\u000aTo ''find the generic or chemical name'' of a drug, you can check the National Institutes of Health's [[MedlinePlus website|http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginformation.html]]. It may be somewhat trickier to find out the drug's brand name in your host country, but [[this tool|https://members.geobluestudents.com/TranslationTools/DrugEquivalents]] from Vanderbilt's international health insurance provider will provide answers in most cases (requires you to have already been enrolled in GeoBlue, in order to have an account for online access--GEO will enroll you prior to departure.).\u000a\u000aWhatever the legal status of your medications, ''request a letter from your physician'' explaining why the drugs you are transporting have been prescribed to you. Also include over-the-counter drugs if needed. You will want to take this letter with you //whenever you travel!// Request that your doctor use the local brand names or generic/chemical names for your drugs.\u000a\u000aWhen possible, ''take enough medicine with you to cover your entire stay abroad'', unless your doctor prefers that you identify a physician in your host country to renew your prescription. You may discuss with your physician and program staff how you will obtain enough medication for your stay. Please be aware that medications //cannot be sent through the mail!//\u000a\u000a|box|k\u000a|!Resources|\u000a|[[Vanderbilt's Office of Global Safety|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/global/global-safety/]], for personal guidance on health and wellness as well as personalized safety guidance for all travelers|\u000a|[[MedlinePlus|http://www.nlm.nih.gov/medlineplus/druginformation.html]], information on prescription and over-the-counter drugs, including generic/chemical names|\u000a|[[GeoBlue Drug Translation Guide|https://members.geobluestudents.com/TranslationTools/DrugEquivalents]], offers equivalent brand names and availability for frequently visited countries/destinations; you will need to already be registered into your GeoBlue insurance and have a GeoBlue account to access|\u000a|[[Directory of Foreign Embassies|https://travel.state.gov/content/travel/en/consularnotification/ConsularNotificationandAccess.html]], US Department of State|\u000a|[[Traveler's Checklist|http://travel.state.gov/content/passports/english/go/checklist.html]] from the US Department of State|\u000a|[[The Yellow Book|http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/yellowbook/2014/table-of-contents]], the CDC's extensive guide for foreign travel, with answers to questions you didn't even know to ask!|\u000a\u000a<<segue "Medical insurance">>\u005c
