V!Before you leave\u000a!!!!Know where you are medically before you depart\u000aRegardless of whether you have an existing medical condition, there are a few things you should do before you go abroad. Feel free to schedule an appointment with [[Vanderbilt's Office of Global Safety|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/global/global-safety/]] to talk through your situation based on your destination and the best steps for your individual wellbeing.\u000a\u000aFirst, consult with a travel medicine clinic (such as the one at the [[VU Student Health Center|https://medschool.vanderbilt.edu/student-health/travel-medicine]]) about any ''vaccinations'' that might be necessary or advisable. You should do this as soon as possible!\u000a\u000aMeet with your medical, dental, and other care providers for a ''full checkup''. You don't want to be blindsided by an unrecognized condition when you arrive in your new location.\u000a\u000aIf you have an existing medical or mental health condition, have an honest discussion with your care providers about your current history and ''how study abroad will fit into your care plan''. Talk with your care provider about a prescription that will last the entire duration of your program.\u000a\u000aConsult with [[Vanderbilt's Office of Global Safety|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/global/global-safety/]] to discuss how international insurance will cover any appointments or prescriptions you may require abroad. The  Office of Global Safety can also assist you in ''setting up appointments in advance'' since there can be very long wait times for appointments in high-enrollment locations and at certain times of the year.\u000a\u000aWhile you know your history, your program staff does not. In an emergency, you may not be able to relay information that is critical to your care. Please ''consider disclosing any physical or mental health conditions'' to your program staff prior to arrival. You can <<if $facultyled or $vanderbilt>>turn in a copy of the Medical Information Form from your GEO account to your faculty leader or resident director<<else>>use the program's medical history form<</if>>, or send an email detailing your history and current care plan.\u000a\u000aLearn the generic names and legal status of any ''prescription medications'' you take //before// you leave the US. In some cases, GEO may be able to advise you on whether your prescriptions are legal to carry abroad. If not, we will help direct you to the appropriate embassy to confirm this information. Contact your GEO advisor or [[Vanderbilt's Office of Global Safety|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/global/global-safety/]].\u000a\u000aEven if your medication(s) are legal, request a letter from your physician explaining your use of prescription and over-the-counter drugs to ensure that you will be allowed entry into your host country.\u000a\u000aWork with the travel clinic mental health team to ''identify resources for obtaining your prescriptions'' in your host country. Your provider may want you to obtain<<if not $shortterm>> monthly<</if>> prescriptions in the host country, and you may also need to have resources available in case you lose your medications.\u000a\u000a<<sidebar-box>>\u000a   [[Do I need any vaccinations?|Vaccinations]]\u000a   [[How do I find out more about my medications?|Where to find crucial information about your medications]]\u000a   [[Should I really disclose my medical information?|Disclosing medical information]]\u000a<</sidebar-box>>\u000a\u000a<<segue "Medical insurance">>
