V!Illness abroad\u000a!!!!Know attendance policies and who to contact\u000aThink about who can best help you if you are sick or injured while abroad. It will usually be someone on site, with your <<if $facultyled>>faculty leader<<else>>program's resident director or staff<</if>> at the top of the list.\u000a\u000aWhen you arrive at your program site, you should receive a list of all appropriate emergency contacts for your program<<if not $facultyled>> or host university<</if>>, as well as for emergency services (police, ambulance, etc.). If you don't receive this information, ask for it! Also consider recording it on GEO's [[handy wallet-sized card|$emergencyCardURL]].\u000a\u000aIf your program doesn't have resident staff, or if it isn't practical to reach them in an emergency, you should call ''Vanderbilt Incident Response for Travel'' (VIRT). [[VIRT|http://www.vanderbilt.edu/global/virt]] is Vanderbilt's 24/7 emergency response service. They can help you coordinate support services and get you the help you need. If you need VIRT's help but it is not an emergency, you can email [[virt@vanderbilt.edu|mailto:virt@vanderbilt.edu]].\u000a\u000aRemember that phone numbers for emergency services will be different in each country you might visit. [[Get the 911 equivalent(s)|$local911URL]] for your destination and save them into your cell phone before you take a side trip.\u000a\u000aBe aware of <<if $facultyled>>your instructor's absence and illness policies.<<else>>the absence and illness policies for your program or host university. They may differ drastically from Vanderbilt policies--and remember that it is your program's policies that you are primarily subject to.<</if>> Always keep your program staff in the loop while ill (via email or phone). \u000a\u000aBe sure to keep any doctor's notes for your files. You may need them later for academic or medical reasons.\u000a\u000a|box|k\u000a|!Resources|\u000a|[[The Yellow Book|http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/yellowbook/2014/table-of-contents]], the CDC's extensive guide for foreign travel, with answers to questions you didn't even know to ask!|\u000a|[[Emergency services numbers abroad|$local911URL]], the US Department of State's list of 911 equivalents around the world|\u000a|[[Vanderbilt Incident Response for Travel|http://www.vanderbilt.edu/global/virt]], Vanderbilt's 24/7 emergency response for travelers|\u000a|[[Vanderbilt's University Counseling Center|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/ucc/]], wherever you are in the world, the PCC can help you identify local resources. When you contact PCC, request the GEO Resource Provider.|\u000a|[[Vanderbilt's Office of Global Safety|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/global/global-safety/]], for personal guidance on international insurance, health and wellness, and safety for all travelers|\u000a\u000a<<segue "Getting there and back again">>\u005c
