V<<sidebar "More on credit cards">>\u000aEurope and much of the rest of the world have long used chip-and-PIN \u201csmart\u201d credit cards. These cards offer more secure transactions by adding an embedded microchip and replacing easily forged signatures with entry of a PIN number.\u000a\u000aWhile US cards all now have chips, a small proportion of overseas processing machines may not be compatible with the US version of the technology. To maximize payment convenience, ''learn the PIN numbers for any credit cards //and// debit cards'' you bring with you.\u000a\u000a''Self-service kiosks are the main culprit for difficulties,'' and may not work even if you do know your US-issued card\u2019s PIN. If you are traveling via train or bus, plan to arrive a little early so that you can find a cashier if need be, and carry cash as well so that you have an alternate form of payment if required. Other places self-service machines might be required are at luggage lockers, bike-rental kiosks, highway tolls, etc.\u000a\u000aIf you are using a credit card, be sure that you are making a simple payment rather than a cash advance. Cash advances can result in high transaction and interest payments.\u000a\u000aYou may want to ''shop around for banks and credit cards'' before you leave. Seek out cards that carry low foreign transaction fees, as well as debit card providers with overseas partnerships that allow for lower ATM fees.\u000a\u000a<<segue "Where will you live?">>
