V!Preparing for safety\u000a!!!!Research your destination and register your travel\u000a<div class="talkbox">\u000a|box|k\u000a|!COVID-19 Considerations|\u000a|The ''coronavirus epidemic continues to present challenges worldwide''. Your program will provide operating procedures, guidelines, and updates while you are abroad. It is critical that you heed this advice and adhere to your program's policies as well as your locality's requirements. Disciplinary action from your program and legal action from local authorities are real possibilities.|\u000a|Most countries outside the United States have taken more nationalized and often more stringent approaches to COVID-19 measures. You are likely to find somewhat different COVID rules and more nuance in how those are applied. In particular, ''response to COVID outbreaks is more likely to involve strict, if temporary, lockdowns and targeted shutdown of services''. These may cause inconvenience, including interrupting classes or travel. It is possible that your coursework might need to go online for an extended period, or that a planned trip may have to be canceled.|\u000a|Requirements and restrictions imposed by the US government, foreign governments, regional governments, airlines, or other entities may change at any time. ''You are ultimately responsible for being aware of and taking action'' to ensure that you meet all these requirements.|\u000a|Students who are not vaccinated against COVID-19 may face additional obstacles such as, for example, the requirement to undergo regular testing in order to participate in many activities. ''Governments may not recognize all types of COVID vaccines as fulfilling requirements''--be sure to check whether your vaccine is recognized. Also check whether your proof of vaccination (CDC card, etc.) will be accepted by all countries you hope to spend time in.|\u000a|It is possible that ''governments may impose vaccination (or other) requirements'', including booster shots, at any time.|\u000a</div>\u000aWhile generally not more dangerous than life in Nashville, study abroad is not a risk-free activity. You are traveling into an unfamiliar country and situation, and the most effective way to avoid problems is to plug the gaps in your knowledge.\u000a\u000aThe more you know and learn about your destination before you go, the safer you will be. Read all the program information you are given, attend the Office of Global Safety's orientation (see below), and do your own research as well. Up-to-date commercial guidebooks are often good resources, particularly for coverage of local risks and high-crime areas. Country-specific information provided by the US Department of State and its counterparts overseas can also be helpful.\u000a\u000aKnow the local laws, and learn about behavioral norms and expectations. Outspokenness and ostentatious public behavior are not virtues in most places abroad. In some situations they may invite unwanted attention and problems. Dress in a fashion that is appropriate to cultural norms and religious sensitivities.\u000a\u000aYour main destination will be automatically registered with  Vanderbilt's emergency evacuation provider (Anvil Group).\u000a\u000aIf you are a US citizen, also ''register with the Department of State's [[STEP program|https://step.state.gov/step/]]'', which allows the US Embassy in your host country to contact you with updates, both before, during, and after an emergency. \u000a\u000a''If you are not a US citizen,'' you can still utilize publicly available resources from the US Department of State, such as online updates. You can also seek out comparable resources from your home country. If your home country has an embassy or consulate near your study abroad site, we recommend that you make note of the contact information.\u000a\u000aFinally, be sure to enter the phone number for Vanderbilt Incident Response for Travel (VIRT) into your mobile phone: ''+1 615-322-2745''. VIRT provides round-the-clock health and safety assistance to Vanderbilt community members around the world.\u000a\u000a|box|k\u000a|!Global Safety Pre-Departure Session|\u000a|''Date and time to be determined''|\u000a| Via Zoom |\u000a|This is a mandatory session with the Office of Global Safety, and you will need to attend in order to maintain eligibility to study abroad. Email [[globalsafety@vanderbilt.edu|mailto:globalsafety@vanderbilt.edu]] if you have questions you'd like to see addressed in the session.|\u000a\u000a<<sidebar-box>>\u000a   [[What are some resources for monitoring regional safety overseas?|Resources for monitoring regional safety]]\u000a   [[How does Vanderbilt minimize risks that students face abroad?|Vanderbilt\u2019s safety efforts]]\u000a<</sidebar-box>>\u005c\u000a\u000a<<segue "Basic safety abroad">>\u005c
