V!Personal emergencies\u000a!!!!What to do after experiencing a personal emergency\u000aPersonal emergencies may arise from illness, accidents, behavioral health crises, or criminal/negligent behavior. They generally require immediate assistance, whether from a health professional, law enforcement, a counselor, or some combination of these. If you encounter a personal emergency abroad, follow these steps:\u000a\u000a''Request help immediately''. Know the local [[emergency number or numbers|$local911URL]] (911 doesn't work abroad!) and have your phone with you at all times. You may download GEO's [[wallet-sized emergency numbers directory|$emergencyCardURL]] to record information in a handy, portable format.\u000a\u000a''Notify your program's emergency contact''. <<if $facultyled>>Your faculty leader or another designated person <<else>>On most programs, at least one member of your program's staff <</if>>will be available to you around the clock. On-site personnel are best positioned to provide timely and appropriate emergency support. If you are reporting an emergency on behalf of a friend, be sure to identify yourself as well as your friend.\u000a\u000aIf you are in immediate danger, ''contact law enforcement as soon as possible''. If you are considering reporting something less immediate to law enforcement, contact your <<if $facultyled>>faculty leader or other designated contact <<else>>program staff <</if>>first. They may be in a better position to talk with law enforcement<<if not $facultyled>>, and will also know the proper protocols<</if>>. Work with them if at all possible. If you do not have access to resident program staff, contact Vanderbilt Incident Response for Travel (VIRT) at +1 615-322-2745.\u000a\u000a''Contact your insurance provider'' if the emergency requires medical attention of any kind. This may be Vanderbilt's international health insurance provider (GeoBlue) or a provider utilized by your program abroad.\u000a\u000a''Notify Vanderbilt Incident Response for Travel'' (VIRT). [[VIRT|http://www.vanderbilt.edu/global/virt]] is Vanderbilt's 24/7 emergency response service. They can help you coordinate support services and get you the help you need.\u000a\u000a''Contact the nearest embassy''. Consular agents at US embassies are available 24/7 to help US citizens with emergencies. If you are not a US citizen, contact both the US embassy (tell them you are a student at a US university) and your home country's embassy.\u000a\u000a''Contact your family''. Your family will be anxious and concerned about your well-being. Your program staff <<if not $facultyled>>and GEO are both<<else>>are<</if>> limited in the information they can share, so be sure to communicate with your family directly if you can.\u000a\u000a<<segue "Large-scale emergencies">>\u005c
