V<<sidebar "Immersing yourself">>\u000aYour study abroad experience can be even more exceptional if you really make the effort to immerse yourself in your new surroundings. Whether you capitalize on what your program offers or create your own opportunities, taking steps to make the most of your time overseas//will//pay off.\u000a\u000aThe study abroad alumni profiled below pursued research, internships, volunteering, and cultural experiences that have led to better career preparation, improved self-knowledge, and more advanced cross-cultural skills. How will //you// engage?\u000a\u000a!!!!I volunteered with Starfish, a service organization for trafficked women\u000aWhile studying in Beijing, I volunteered with the Starfish Project, a service organization that works with previously trafficked women. Starfish teaches vocational skills and provides continuing education and health care access. I taught English. Our English Corner, a regular group discussion in both Chinese and English on a variety of topics, gave me a fantastic opportunity to be involved in the exchange of cultures. Coming back to Vanderbilt, I decided to put more effort into immersing myself at home as well: I teach Spanish at the Tennessee Foreign Language Institute, tutor in Chinese, and am looking forward to a future with strong connections to the global community.\u000a\u000aOmega Tennant\u000aCET Beijing, Spring 2013\u000aMajor: Human & Organizational Development\u000a\u000a!!!!I prepared for the experience I wanted to have--and interned at the Vienna State Opera\u000a\u000aI wanted to go to Vienna, but I knew I'd get much more out of it if I knew the language. So I went to summer language school beforehand, and with that grasp of German I was able to make local friends and attend Universitt Wien. When I somehow managed to become the (first-ever!) intern at the Vienna State Opera, it was a dream come true. In addition to learning the art and business of opera at one of the most important cultural institutions in the world, I got to see Austrian work and daily life from the inside. I fell in love with Vienna, and will be returning after graduation to make a life there.\u000a\u000aNora Pertz\u000aIES Vienna, Spring 2014\u000aMajors: Piano Performance, European Studies\u000a\u000a<<segue "Before you leave">>\u005c
