V<<sidebar "Traveling with a musical instrument">>\u000aAir travel with a musical instrument can present special challenges. Many instruments are larger than the typical carry-on bag, and some are irregularly shaped. Certain instruments are fragile, exceptionally valuable, or contain protected materials. Here are some things to consider as you decide whether and how to bring your instrument.\u000a\u000aIf you have a large instrument, or a very valuable one, you may want to check into options for ''renting an instrument'' rather than dealing with transport. Contact your program provider or GEO to see whether renting is a viable option. \u000a\u000aThe airline you choose may greatly affect your transportation options. Check their ''guidelines for checked and carry-on baggage''. Some airlines allow 1-2 checked bags for no charge, while others charge even for a single checked bag. If your instrument is too large, you may be able to ''buy a seat next to you''. <<if $semester>>If you receive financial assistance, you may want to check with the Office of Financial Aid to see whether help might be available to cover the second seat.<</if>>\u000a\u000aOn full flights, airlines may require that carry-on items be checked. Arriving early to get through security and/or paying for advance boarding may help avoid this situation. But even if you plan to carry on your instrument, it is wise to ''pack it as though it will be checked''.\u000a\u000a''Pack your instrument'' in a hard-sided case with padding around it;  foam, bubble wrap, newspapers, and t-shirts work well as packing materials. Put a tag with your name, permanent address, and phone number both outside and inside your case. Include short instructions in case a security officer is handling and repacking your instrument.\u000a\u000aIt is also vitally important that you check to see if your instrument contains any [[protected materials|https://www.fws.gov/international/permits/by-activity/musical-instruments.html]] such as Brazilian rosewood, elephant ivory, tortoiseshell, or other rare plant or animal material. Some materials require [[special documentation or a permit|http://americanorchestras.org/advocacy-government/travel-with-instruments/endangered-species-material/protected-species-travel-tips.html]], and if carrying them you must travel through [[specific ports|http://americanorchestras.org/advocacy-government/travel-with-instruments/endangered-species-material/protected-species-travel-tips/designated-ports-of-entry-exit.html]].\u000a\u000aBefore you make final decisions about bringing a large instrument, you may want to check with your program provider to see what options you will have for ''instrument storage''. \u000a\u000a<<<\u000a''Predeparture checklist''\u000a\u000a<ul class="checklist">\u005c\u000a<li><<smartcheckbox "$todo.instrumentProtected">>Check whether your instrument contains [[protected materials|https://www.fws.gov/international/pdf/factsheet-musical-instruments.pdf]] that require [[special documentation, a permit|http://americanorchestras.org/advocacy-government/travel-with-instruments/endangered-species-material/protected-species-travel-tips.html]], or travel through [[specific ports|http://americanorchestras.org/advocacy-government/travel-with-instruments/endangered-species-material/protected-species-travel-tips/designated-ports-of-entry-exit.html]].</li>\u000a<li><<smartcheckbox "$todo.instrumentStorage">>Inquire with your program provider about storing your instrument safely while abroad. Consider bringing a lock for safe storage.</li>\u000a<li><<smartcheckbox "$todo.instrumentRental">>Look into options for renting an instrument abroad.</li>\u000a<li><<smartcheckbox "$todo.instrumentCarry">>Check your airline\u2019s carry-on limits and measure your instrument case to see if it will fit on all flights.</li>\u000a<li><<smartcheckbox "$todo.instrumentDecision">>Decide whether to carry on or check your instrument on your flight(s).</li>\u000a<li><<smartcheckbox "$todo.instrumentPacking">>Pack and label your instrument, preferably so that if carry-on compartments are full and your instrument has to be checked at the gate, it will be protected.</li>\u000a<li><<smartcheckbox "$todo.instrumentArrival">>If carrying on your instrument, arrive early to your flight and/or consider paying for advance boarding.</li></ul>\u000a<<<\u000a|box|k\u000a|!Resources|\u000a|[[US Department of Transportation|http://www.transportation.gov/airconsumer/tips-traveling-musical-instrument]] provides helpful information, tips, and frequently asked questions about traveling with musical instruments.|\u000a|[[Airlines for America|http://airlines.org/blog/instrument-rated-air-travel-for-musicians/]], the airline industry trade association, outlines a list of the instrument policies for all major carriers.|\u000a|Instructions on musical instruments from specific airlines: [[United|https://www.united.com/ual/en/us/fly/travel/baggage/fragile.html#Musicalinstruments]], [[Delta|https://www.delta.com/us/en/baggage/special-items/musical-instruments]], [[American|https://www.aa.com/i18n/travelInformation/baggage/specialty-sports.jsp]], [[British Airways|https://www.britishairways.com/en-us/information/baggage-essentials/musical-instruments]], [[easyJet|http://www.easyjet.com/en/music-instruments]], [[Jet Blue|https://www.jetblue.com/help/musical-instruments-and-other-special-items]]|\u000a|[[Future of Music Coalition|http://www.futureofmusic.org/article/fact-sheet/traveling-instruments]] offers suggestions and tips from a musician's perspective.|\u000a|[[Details about permits and international travel with protected materials|https://www.fws.gov/international/permits/by-activity/musical-instruments.html]] from US Fish and Wildlife.|\u000a|[[Information on protected materials permits|http://americanorchestras.org/advocacy-government/travel-with-instruments/endangered-species-material/protected-species-travel-tips.html]] from the League of American Orchestras.|\u000a|[[Tips on packing|http://flyingwithguitars.com/2013/08/packing-guitars/]], specifically guitars but generalizable to other instruments.|\u000a\u000a<<segue "Passport Check">>
