V<<sidebar "Transgender travelers">>\u000aTransgender students are valued members of the Vanderbilt community. Abroad, attitudes regarding transgender students may not be the same. Cultures may not support or value ''non-cisnormative genders or non-heteronormative sexualities'', and in some countries transgender people may face criminal sanctions simply because they are transgender. Before you travel abroad, ''learn more about the laws, customs, and attitudes'' of the country in which you will be studying. Some resources are provided at the end of this article as a starting point.\u000a\u000aWhen preparing to travel, be sure that your documents and IDs match your legal name and gender. We recognize this process can be anxiety-inducing and stressful for trans people; however, due to the legal system of the United States, ''the name, gender, and date of birth on your flight ticket must match the government-issued photo ID (i.e. passport) you provide when passing through security''. Perceived differences between documents and gender presentation may cause delays and/or additional screenings by travel agency staff. \u000a\u000aIf your US passport does not reflect your current gender, you can [[obtain a new ten-year passport with your updated gender|https://transequality.org/know-your-rights/passports]] but you must provide a ''letter from your physician'' documenting appropriate \u201cclinical treatment\u201d for gender transition. ''If you have decided to engage in the process of gender transition'', you can [[obtain a temporary two-year passport with your updated gender|https://transequality.org/know-your-rights/passports]]. If your passport does not match your gender/has not been updated to reflect your gender, you ''must apply in person'' at any passport acceptance facility. If you are applying for a change of name, you may be eligible to apply by mail. Consult [[details|https://transequality.org/know-your-rights/passports]] provided by the National Center for Transgender Equality. If you are not a US citizen, consult the embassy or consulate of your home country for requirements.\u000a\u000aWhen traveling, be aware that ''security screening'' may involve whole-body scanners (Advanced Imaging Technology) or a pat-down. If you opt out of the imaging scan, or if the machine detects something \u201cunusual\u201d (such as ''binding garments, prosthetics, or body parts the attendant did not assume you to have''), you will be required to go through a ''pat-down''. The officer working will assign an officer they assume matches your gender to perform the pat-down. Travelers may ''ask for a private screening'' at any time, and you may bring a travel companion in with you. You should never be required to lift or remove an article of clothing to reveal your body part(s) or a prosthetic item. If you use a prosthetic item, you are not required to remove it. \u000a\u000aIf you are carrying any ''medically prescribed items with you, bring documentation from your physician''. If you are on ''hormones'', talk with your physician about how to access medical treatment and prescriptions abroad. \u000a\u000aBe aware that traveling within your host country or crossing borders while abroad may also require documentation and security screenings.\u000a\u000aWhen planning for your trip, consider ''housing options'' that fit your comfort and safety levels. Single rooms might be best for personal freedom, but they may not be available or may cost more. It may be wise to talk to your program provider to seek trans-friendly roommates or host families. \u000a\u000aAfter considering potential safety issues, determine how you would like instructors and peers abroad to address you, for example with your ''preferred name and gender pronouns''. You may want to ask your program provider about the availability of ''gender inclusive restrooms''.\u000a\u000aIf you have any questions or concerns, feel free to [[contact GEO|https://vanderbilt.edu/geo/advising/]] and we will be happy to help you work through them.\u000a\u000a|box|k\u000a|!Resources|\u000a|[[International Lesbian Gay Bisexual Trans and Intersex Association|https://davidson.studioabroad.com/_customtags/ct_FileRetrieve.cfm?File_ID=05077A7671743F0777067173060A011C7C0D777C1A0C0307051C7174050501730706777D71707171020D]] (ILGA) provides a country-by-country analysis of attitudes and laws regarding LGBTQ people; not focused on transgender issues, but possibly broadly useful.|\u000a|More information on the new [[passport gender change policy|http://www.transequality.org/sites/default/files/docs/kyr/passports_2014.pdf]] for US passport holders.|\u000a|How to [[apply for a limited 2-year US passport|https://travel.state.gov/content/travel/en/passports/apply-renew-passport/gender.html]] if you are in the process of gender transition.|\u000a|The National Center for Transgender Equality (NCTE) provides an [[ID Documents Center|http://www.transequality.org/documents]] to help you get a legal name change and update your name/gender on state and federal IDs and records.|\u000a|NCTE offers a [[\u201cKnow Your Rights\u201d report|http://www.transequality.org/sites/default/files/docs/kyr/AirportSecurity_March2014.pdf]] on airport security and transgender people.|\u000a|If you do experience disrespectful treatment or other problems from airline staff, you may [[file a complaint|https://www.transportation.gov/airconsumer/file-consumer-complaint]] with the Aviation Consumer Protection Division.|\u000a|Check out a blog post on a [[Transgender Guide to Staying Safe While Traveling.|http://dopesontheroad.com/travel/transgender-guide-to-staying-safe-while-traveling/]]|\u000a|If you have a smart phone and are traveling within the U.S. or Europe, you can download the REFUGE Restroom app to help you locate gender inclusive restrooms.|\u000a|[[GEO's Global Safety and Security Manager|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/geo/advising#safetyadvising]], for personal guidance on safety and wellbeing for all travelers|\u000a\u000a<<segue "Contacts and communications">>\u005c
