V!How to use international health insurance\u000a!!!!The basics of networks and claims\u000a\u000aMost international health insurers have their own network of partner clinics and hospitals around the world. When you use one of these <span title="A clinic is 'in-network' if the insurer has identified it as a preferred partner and has set up a direct billing relationship with the clinic.">in-network</span> clinics, billing should be straightforward: If the care you receive requires a <span title="A co-pay is the amount, usually expressed as a percentage, that the patient pays. The remainder is paid by the insurance company.">co-pay</span>, you will pay that to the clinic, usually on the day of your appointment. The clinic will then bill the balance to the insurer directly. You can find information on what percentage your insurer pays for different types of medical expenses in the insurer\u2019s guide to benefits.\u000a\u000a''What happens if it isn\u2019t convenient to visit an in-network clinic?''\u000aIf you can\u2019t visit an in-network clinic for any of your insurers, GEO recommends that you contact Vanderbilt\u2019s international health insurer (GeoBlue). You can call or email GeoBlue a few days in advance of an appointment and request that they set up a direct payment relationship with the provider.\u000a\u000aIf GeoBlue isn\u2019t able to set up direct payment, or you aren\u2019t able to call them ahead of time, don\u2019t worry. You can go to any medical establishment abroad, pay out of pocket, and then submit a claim to GeoBlue (remember to keep all your receipts!). If you need help with this process, please [[contact VIRT|mailto:virt@vanderbilt.edu]].\u000a\u000a''How do you decide which plan to use?''\u000aYou might have multiple insurance policies available while you\u2019re abroad. All students on GEO programs will have Vanderbilt\u2019s international insurance. Your study abroad program may have its own insurance that will also cover you, and students who are on exchange programs may also be required to purchase specific national health insurance. Here's how you can approach this:\u000a\u000a# Compare your coverage across the different policies: If one policy covers you for a specific condition and another does not, that is important information. It\u2019s also important to know whether the co-pays differ between insurance policies. If one covers you at 100%, but the other has a 20% co-pay, you will probably want to submit for reimbursement under the policy that grants full coverage.\u000a# If your program purchases specific health insurance on your behalf, your program staff probably has a good working knowledge of that insurer and its network of providers. Consult with them to get a good sense of where to go for treatment.\u000a# You can always use the coverage from Vanderbilt\u2019s international insurer (GeoBlue). If you do, VIRT is available to help you come to terms with the process.\u000a\u000a|box|k\u000a|!Resources|\u000a|Before you leave: [[Vanderbilt's Office of Global Safety|https://www.vanderbilt.edu/global/global-safety/]], for personal guidance on internation insurance, health and wellness, and safety for all travelers|\u000a|While you're abroad: [[Contact VIRT|mailto:virt@vanderbilt.edu]] to inquire about using Vanderbilt\u2019s international health insurance to access medical services|\u000a|[[Brief coverage and services description|https://geo.vanderbilt.edu/_customtags/ct_FileRetrieve.cfm?File_ID=2361]] for Vanderbilt\u2019s international health insurer|\u000a|[[Detailed description of coverage|https://geo.vanderbilt.edu/_customtags/ct_FileRetrieve.cfm?File_ID=15554]] for Vanderbilt\u2019s international health insurer|\u000a|[[General guide to medical care and insurance|http://www.studentsabroad.com/handbook/medical-care-and-insurance.php?country=General]] from StudentsAbroad.com|\u000a\u000a<<segue "Culture shock">>\u005c\u000a\u000a
